<DOC><DOCNO> AP890208-0205 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-08-89 2140EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-Bush-Cabinet     02-08 0140</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Bush-Cabinet,140</SECOND><HEAD>Bush To Remain Two Councils</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Bush has decided to retain twoCabinet-level councils set up by former President Reagan, onedealing with domestic and the other with economic policy, the WhiteHouse said Wednesday.   A statement issued by the office of White House Press SecretaryMarlin Fitzwater said that Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady wouldgenerally preside over the the Economic Policy Committee andAttorney General Richard Thornburgh over the Domestic Policy Council.   The economic unit is made up of the secretaries of State,Treasury, Agriculture, Commerce, Labor, budget director, the U.S.trade representative and the chairman of the Council of EconomicAdvisers.   The domestic unit is made up of the secretaries of Interior,Health and Human Services, Housing and Urban Develop, Energy,Education, Veterans Affairs, the budget director and theEnvironmental Protection Agency.</TEXT></DOC>